00:04:27.280 --> 00:04:32.280
Okay, so let me just review some things and&nbsp;
introduce a slight variant to things that we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:32.280 --> 00:04:39.360
already know about. So, we know that a natural&nbsp;
number is a box of zeros. Zero is just an empty&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:39.360 --> 00:04:44.400
box. There’s a zero; there's a zero. Now, here's&nbsp;
a box with two zeros in it—that's what we think&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:44.400 --> 00:04:49.560
of as being the number two. Here’s a box with&nbsp;
one zero in it—that's what we think of as being&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:49.560 --> 00:04:57.080
the number one. Okay, that’s very familiar,&nbsp;
I hope. Let’s introduce a slight variant of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:57.080 --> 00:05:04.720
that which is particularly useful when we&nbsp;
are thinking about the carrot operation.

00:05:06.800 --> 00:05:15.280
So, a natural star number—this is a new&nbsp;
definition, and whether it should be like this or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:15.280 --> 00:05:21.760
maybe natural to the star, I won’t fuss around too&nbsp;
much about what the actual terminology is. We’ll&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:21.760 --> 00:05:28.920
just loosely talk about it this way for now. What&nbsp;
this thing is, is a non-empty box of zeros. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:28.920 --> 00:05:35.120
when we’re talking about natural numbers, this&nbsp;
thing here qualifies as a natural number because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:35.120 --> 00:05:42.560
it’s a box of zeros which happens to be empty.&nbsp;
When we go to nat star, we want to exclude the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:42.560 --> 00:05:51.760
zero. So we want to start counting from one: 1,&nbsp;
2, 3. Here we’re counting from 0, 1, 2, 3. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:51.760 --> 00:05:56.080
in mathematics, there’s this dichotomy about&nbsp;
whether in a given situation you should start&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:56.080 --> 00:06:01.960
counting with zero or start counting with one,&nbsp;
and in different situations, either of those&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:01.960 --> 00:06:08.120
could be maybe more apt, more convenient.&nbsp;
What we’re doing here is just introducing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:08.120 --> 00:06:14.040
some alternate notation so that in those cases&nbsp;
where it’s more convenient to count starting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:14.040 --> 00:06:21.680
with one, that we have some pre-existing&nbsp;
notation for that. So that’s nat star.

00:06:21.680 --> 00:06:26.680
And then, when we go down a level to poly,&nbsp;
I remind you that a poly is a box of natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:26.680 --> 00:06:32.160
numbers, natural numbers in this sense here. So&nbsp;
let’s define poly star to be a box of natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:32.160 --> 00:06:42.400
star numbers. So a poly star is like a poly except&nbsp;
that when you look inside the box at the natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:42.400 --> 00:06:49.120
numbers that are appearing in there, you don’t&nbsp;
find any zeros. Okay, so that’s a poly star.

00:06:49.120 --> 00:06:56.200
Okay, so let’s have a look at poly star. All&nbsp;
right, these are poly numbers that don’t have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:56.200 --> 00:07:05.520
any zeros inside them. So here’s A and here&nbsp;
is B. These are both poly star numbers. It’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:05.520 --> 00:07:10.880
a box of natural numbers. You recognize&nbsp;
this is the natural number one, this is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:10.880 --> 00:07:14.560
the natural number one, this is the natural&nbsp;
number three. Here’s the natural number one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:14.560 --> 00:07:18.920
here’s the natural number two. So these are&nbsp;
both boxes of natural numbers, but they’re&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:18.920 --> 00:07:25.600
natural star numbers because there are no zeros&nbsp;
in these boxes. In other words, there are no&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:25.600 --> 00:07:31.800
empty boxes by themselves as elements. So let me&nbsp;
just remind you about the basic three operations.

00:07:31.800 --> 00:07:37.600
Addition is just dumping all the entries into a&nbsp;
new box. So A plus B is just this thing here in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:37.600 --> 00:07:44.720
the obvious fashion. A times B, the way we get&nbsp;
that is we form all possible combinations of an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:44.720 --> 00:07:50.440
element in A and an element in B and we add those&nbsp;
two elements. So if we add this and this, we get&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:50.440 --> 00:07:55.800
this. This and this, we get this. This and this,&nbsp;
we get this. This and this, we get this. This and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:55.800 --> 00:08:03.240
this, we get this. And this and this, we get this.&nbsp;
Okay, so that’s the product of these two boxes.

00:08:03.240 --> 00:08:11.240
And then we have the carrot operation. Okay,&nbsp;
so the carrot of two boxes is the box you get&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:11.240 --> 00:08:19.000
by taking elements in A and elements&nbsp;
in B and now multiplying them. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:26.240
multiplying them, not adding them as we did&nbsp;
for the multiplication. So this times this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:26.240 --> 00:08:30.320
well, this is one and this is one, so one&nbsp;
times one is one. And one times two is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:30.320 --> 00:08:35.160
two. And one times one is one. And one&nbsp;
times two is two. And three times one is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:35.160 --> 00:08:44.840
three. And three times two is six.&nbsp;
So there is the carrot of A and B.

00:08:44.840 --> 00:08:50.880
And let’s just remind ourselves that we have a&nbsp;
kind of distributive property. First of all, both&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:50.880 --> 00:08:57.760
these properties are commutative and both of them&nbsp;
are associative. But what about distributivity?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:57.760 --> 00:09:03.720
Well, both of them are distributive with&nbsp;
respect to addition. So A times B plus C&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:03.720 --> 00:09:16.040
is A times B plus A times C. And also A carrot&nbsp;
B plus C equals A carrot B plus A carrot C. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:16.040 --> 00:09:23.880
in terms of doing algebra, we might say,&nbsp;
okay, in this domain of just poly stars,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:23.880 --> 00:09:28.440
we could look at the familiar operations of&nbsp;
addition and multiplication, and that would&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:28.440 --> 00:09:33.000
give us the usual polynomial algebra that&nbsp;
we've been thinking about since, you know,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:40.160
at least high school. But we could also do&nbsp;
something that we’re much less familiar with.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:40.160 --> 00:09:50.000
We could look at an algebra formed by considering&nbsp;
addition and the carrot operation because the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:56.240
carrot operation and the addition are related&nbsp;
in this nice way via this distributive law. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:56.240 --> 00:10:02.480
we have commutativity and associativity of both&nbsp;
operations. So, you know, that’s a very natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:02.480 --> 00:10:09.600
thing to think about: what happens, what does&nbsp;
that look like, that sort of algebra structure?

00:10:09.600 --> 00:10:15.920
All right, so we can ask ourselves, what does&nbsp;
this plus-carrot algebra of poly star look like?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:15.920 --> 00:10:21.240
But before we do that, let me answer a natural&nbsp;
question, which is why are we considering poly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:21.240 --> 00:10:27.000
star instead of just poly? Because, after all,&nbsp;
the carrot operation works on polys just as well&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:38.680
as it does on poly stars. Well, here’s the answer.&nbsp;
Suppose you have this poly times this poly. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:38.680 --> 00:10:43.520
the way we multiply them, we just take all&nbsp;
possible sums. So zero plus zero is zero. Zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:43.520 --> 00:10:49.400
plus two is two. One plus zero is one. And one&nbsp;
plus two is three. And three plus zero is three.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:49.400 --> 00:10:55.280
And three plus two is five. Fine. And now suppose&nbsp;
we look at the carrot of these two things. So now&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:55.280 --> 00:11:00.480
we have to multiply things. So zero times zero is&nbsp;
zero. Zero times two is zero. One times zero is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:00.480 --> 00:11:07.040
zero. One times two is two. Three times zero&nbsp;
is zero. And three times two is six. Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:07.040 --> 00:11:13.840
we see that these two zeros here, because we’re&nbsp;
doing a lot of multiplications, mean that we’re&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:13.840 --> 00:11:19.400
getting a lot more zeros at the next stage. And&nbsp;
if we took this thing here and multiplied it by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:19.400 --> 00:11:26.560
some other poly with a zero in it, then the result&nbsp;
would have even more zeros. So these zeros kind of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:26.560 --> 00:11:32.760
reproduce like rabbits, you know, and it’s not&nbsp;
so interesting. It’s just not so interesting.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:32.760 --> 00:11:38.600
So it’s for that reason that we’re going to&nbsp;
restrict ourselves in this little world here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:38.600 --> 00:11:47.520
just to poly stars so that all our poly numbers&nbsp;
start with ones, if anything, there are no zeros.

00:11:47.520 --> 00:11:56.000
So for example, let’s do a bit of arithmetic here.&nbsp;
Let’s take the poly star 1 2 3 and carrot it with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:00.960
itself. So we look at all possible products.&nbsp;
One times one is one. One times two is two.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:00.960 --> 00:12:01.496
One times three is three. Two times one is&nbsp;
two. Two times two is four. Two times three&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:01.496 --> 00:12:08.760
is six. Three times one is three. Three times&nbsp;
two is six. Three times three is nine. We get&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:08.760 --> 00:12:18.200
this box here. And we could a little bit more&nbsp;
efficiently describe that by not repeating all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:18.200 --> 00:12:24.640
the repetitions, but just recording how many of&nbsp;
each of the things there are. So there’s one one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:24.640 --> 00:12:29.320
so we don’t need to say anything, but there’s&nbsp;
two twos, so beside the two, we’ll put a little&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:29.320 --> 00:12:35.200
two to the left. Okay, it means sort of&nbsp;
like two of them. And there’s two threes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:35.200 --> 00:12:42.200
so we’ll put a little two to the left and below&nbsp;
the three. There’s one four, there’s one six,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:42.200 --> 00:12:50.840
and there’s one nine. So this is a little bit&nbsp;
more efficient way of describing that same result.

00:12:50.840 --> 00:12:57.480
Now, if we were going to go down this road, we&nbsp;
could be a little bit more efficient. So what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:57.480 --> 00:13:04.600
we’re really doing here is recording the various&nbsp;
multiplicities that the various possible natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:04.600 --> 00:13:10.720
numbers that are allowed, namely 1 2 3 4 etc.,&nbsp;
are appearing with. Okay, so another way of doing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:10.720 --> 00:13:16.840
this a bit more systematically is to just list all&nbsp;
the natural numbers from 1 to 9 in this case and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:16.840 --> 00:13:22.120
record for each one of them the multiplicity that&nbsp;
we're getting with this thing here. There’s one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:22.120 --> 00:13:26.960
one, there’s two twos, there’s two threes, there’s&nbsp;
one four, there’s zero fives, there’s one six,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:26.960 --> 00:13:32.560
there’s zero sevens, there’s zero eights,&nbsp;
there’s one nine. And when we do that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:32.560 --> 00:13:38.520
we see that essentially another way of&nbsp;
thinking about this box is in terms of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:38.520 --> 00:13:46.720
this list of multiplicities. Okay, it's a list&nbsp;
now because it’s ordered because we’re using the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:46.720 --> 00:13:51.880
fact that our natural numbers are naturally&nbsp;
ordered, starting with one, in this case,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:51.880 --> 00:13:59.440
our natural star numbers, 1 2 3 4 etc. So it&nbsp;
makes sense to just record the multiplicity,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:59.440 --> 00:14:03.760
right? We don’t really need to repeat these&nbsp;
numbers here. We know what they are by their&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:03.760 --> 00:14:13.720
positions. So we just record 1 2 2 1 0 1 0 0&nbsp;
1. And from this, if we wanted to know what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:13.720 --> 00:14:20.120
the multiplicity of five is, we go 1 2 3 4 5.&nbsp;
Ah, there’s zero fives. And how many sixes are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:20.120 --> 00:14:29.240
there? 1 2 3 4 5 6. There’s one six, etc. Okay,&nbsp;
so this is actually quite an important thing that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:29.240 --> 00:14:35.560
we have a multiset on one hand. So this multiset&nbsp;
here, which is unordered, has repetitions,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:35.560 --> 00:14:46.600
can be alternately encoded by a multiplicity list,&nbsp;
which is now a list in the sense that it’s ordered&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:46.600 --> 00:14:54.560
and repetitions are allowed. So this accords&nbsp;
with our general LS, lists, ORD sets, multisets,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:54.560 --> 00:15:01.120
sets sort of notation. We’re using square brackets&nbsp;
to denote lists, like a computer scientist would.

00:15:01.120 --> 00:15:06.640
Okay, so a little bit more formally now, let’s&nbsp;
officially introduce the idea of the multiplicity&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:06.640 --> 00:15:15.960
list or M list of a poly star. So the multiplicity&nbsp;
list or M list of the poly star P. So here it is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:15.960 --> 00:15:20.800
written in the form where we're recording the&nbsp;
number of ones. So there’s a1 ones, there’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:20.800 --> 00:15:27.640
a2 twos, there’s a3 threes, all the way up to say&nbsp;
a sub k k's. This is a poly star because there are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:27.640 --> 00:15:38.240
no zeros. Okay, so that’s a box. It’s an unordered&nbsp;
collection where repetitions are allowed. And now&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:38.240 --> 00:15:44.680
what we’re going to do is introduce this other&nbsp;
data structure, which is a list where we just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:44.680 --> 00:15:52.200
record the numbers or the multiplicities of all&nbsp;
of the natural numbers in order, 1 2 3 all the way&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:52.200 --> 00:15:59.560
up to wherever we’re going. So we record a1 a2 a3&nbsp;
all the way up to a sub k. Let’s call that M of P,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:59.560 --> 00:16:04.840
the multiplicity list of P. P is a poly star. This&nbsp;
is something a little bit different, although it’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:04.840 --> 00:16:11.600
pretty well equivalent to this, right? But it’s&nbsp;
in the form of a list or equivalently a vector,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:11.600 --> 00:16:19.440
pretty well the same thing. So the entries&nbsp;
here are going to be, well, in this case,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:19.440 --> 00:16:24.960
natural numbers, but including zero, right? So&nbsp;
it’s certainly possible for the number of threes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:24.960 --> 00:16:30.400
to be zero. So this thing is going to have zeros&nbsp;
in it. This thing doesn’t have zeros. And it’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:30.400 --> 00:16:34.920
also usual to sort of allow this convention&nbsp;
to be flexible about the end, you know. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:34.920 --> 00:16:41.120
I mean, if the last entry here had happened to be&nbsp;
zero, well, you know, we could in principle get&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:41.120 --> 00:16:47.320
rid of that. So we'll allow ourselves to append&nbsp;
zeros or remove zeros at the end and regard those&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:47.320 --> 00:16:59.040
things as being equal. That makes the addition&nbsp;
operation on poly stars sort of transferable&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:59.040 --> 00:17:03.960
to the vector world, right? Where if you&nbsp;
allow the vectors to have more entries,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:03.960 --> 00:17:08.080
if we’re adding a vector with five&nbsp;
entries and a vector with seven entries,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:08.080 --> 00:17:12.960
we just think of padding that vector with&nbsp;
five entries with the two additional zeros,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:12.960 --> 00:17:17.240
and then they have the same size,&nbsp;
and then we just add component-wise.

00:17:17.240 --> 00:17:24.680
Okay, so now let’s introduce what we&nbsp;
call the carrot convolution of M lists.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:24.680 --> 00:17:29.200
What we’re going to do here is we’re&nbsp;
going to transfer the carrot operation,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:29.200 --> 00:17:37.000
which is on poly stars, to a corresponding&nbsp;
operation on the associated multiplicity&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:43.000
lists. So there's a correspondence between these&nbsp;
poly stars and these multiplicity lists. If we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:46.600
know the poly star, we know the multiplicity&nbsp;
list. If we know the multiplicity list, then we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:46.600 --> 00:17:51.840
can recover the poly star. So they're completely&nbsp;
equivalent. But over here in the poly star world,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:51.840 --> 00:17:59.360
we have this operation of carrot. So we can&nbsp;
just define the operation over here in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:59.360 --> 00:18:07.800
world of lists or vectors to be the corresponding&nbsp;
thing. So formally, if P, Q, and R are poly stars,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:07.800 --> 00:18:20.040
let’s say with P carrot Q equals R, then we’ll&nbsp;
define M of P convolution M of Q to be M of R.&nbsp;&nbsp;

